TY  - JOUR
ID  - 31802934
VL  - 12
Y1  - 2019
T1  - Pain Management In Pediatric Patients With Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia  Syndrome: Current Insights.
SP  - 2969-2980
DO  - 10.2147/JPR.S194391
AB  - Pediatric patients with postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS) often  present with co-occurring struggles with chronic pain (POTS+pain) that may limit  daily activities. POTS is a clinical syndrome characterized by orthostatic  symptoms and excessive postural tachycardia without orthostatic hypotension.  Active research from the medical and scientific community has led to controversy  over POTS diagnosis and treatment, yet patients continue to present with symptoms  associated with POTS+pain, making treatment recommendations critical. This  topical review examines the literature on diagnosing and treating pediatric  POTS+pain and the challenges clinicians face. Most importantly, clinicians must  employ an interdisciplinary team approach to determine the ideal combination of  pharmacologic (e.g., fludrocortisone), non-pharmacologic (e.g., physical therapy,  integrative medicine), and psychological (e.g., cognitive behavioral therapy,  psychoeducation) treatment approaches that acknowledge the complexity of the  child's condition, while simultaneously tailoring these approaches to the child's  personal needs. We provide recommendations for treatment for youth with POTS+pain  based on the current literature.
